---
title: "Practice Quiz - Introduction to R"
---

::: {.cell}

:::

::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


What is the last number produced by `seq(2, 20, by = 3)`?

<input class='webex-solveme nospaces' id='webex-cc79b1b919f2ae5aba462371319dabdd' data-tol='0' size='20' data-answer='OEEFCUBs'/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

The sequence is 2, 5, 8, 11, 14, 17, 20. Because 20 is exactly reached, it is included.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


For `m <- matrix(1:6, nrow = 2)`, what is `m[2,2]`?

<input class='webex-solveme nospaces' id='webex-22a98a2ec4260b18eed9faa41a9f4ae7' data-tol='0' size='20' data-answer='aRBVG2U='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Filled by column, the matrix columns are (1,2), (3,4), (5,6). Row 2, column 2 is 4.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


If `m <- matrix(1:9, nrow = 3)`, what is `ncol(m)`?

<input class='webex-solveme nospaces' id='webex-b5a3b3c65343937dc36f5a047c3666ca' data-tol='0' size='20' data-answer='ORdSET8='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

The command specifies a matrix with three rows. Since you have nine values to populate a 3-row matrix, it follows that the matrix must have three columns.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Write the indexing expression to get the last element of a vector `x`.

<input class='webex-solveme regex' id='webex-dae953eefdd641b01c39d58214266bc9' size='30' data-answer='P0M7ZWlATx06OD9aUV8FRFk/bxEcaWQbbWhvamoRSR1GPA=='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

The last element is at position `length(x)`, so `x[length(x)]` returns it.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Let `x <- c(3, NA, 7)`. What is `sum(x, na.rm = TRUE)`?

<input class='webex-solveme nospaces' id='webex-95c8d3b1d3067cd6e61560d072717df1' data-tol='0' size='20' data-answer='YhdSCEZu'/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

`na.rm = TRUE` removes missing values before summing: 3 + 7 = 10.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Which base R function makes a histogram?

<input class='webex-solveme regex' id='webex-b9fc52dd5bca5168657bc2d66e382ae3' size='23' data-answer='ORs4P2lBTgxcERdJaW0eZGocHl0/bhccEkdu'/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

`hist()` is the function that draws a histogram using base R graphics.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Let `x <- c(1, 2, 3)`. What is `mean(x)`?

<input class='webex-solveme nospaces' id='webex-024d3fb67487578db5b5dbf728851dbe' data-tol='0' size='20' data-answer='axAGRm4='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

The mean is (1 + 2 + 3) / 3 = 2.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


If you run `x <- c(2, 4, 6)`, what type of object is `x`?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-80cc716fc6b1ea08fc23c3c8d0751dd3' data-answer='YwFPUxsBGlY+'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='80cc716fc6b1ea08fc23c3c8d0751dd3'></input><span>a vector</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='80cc716fc6b1ea08fc23c3c8d0751dd3'></input><span>a list</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='80cc716fc6b1ea08fc23c3c8d0751dd3'></input><span>a data frame</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='80cc716fc6b1ea08fc23c3c8d0751dd3'></input><span>a matrix</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

`c()` combines values into a vector, s x is a vector.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Let `x <- 1:10`. What is `sum(x)`?

<input class='webex-solveme nospaces' id='webex-a5f1cf5a1303e882c0864c362468f3d7' data-tol='0' size='20' data-answer='OhdTBEE7'/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

The sum 1+2+...+10 equals 55.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Let `x <- c(10, 20, 30)`. What is `length(x[x > 15])`?

<input class='webex-solveme nospaces' id='webex-a91d2fa2e216388e81d67737c602e3d4' data-tol='0' size='20' data-answer='OhsDRm8='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Values greater than 15 are 20 and 30, giving a vector of length 2.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Which of these are valid ways to create a numeric vector? Select all that apply.


<div class='webex-checkboxgroup' id='webex-0a54624b905011eb400b99e5e2de9435' data-answer='a1EZBRoDGFJk'><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='0a54624b905011eb400b99e5e2de9435'></input><span>`list(1, 2, 3)`</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='0a54624b905011eb400b99e5e2de9435'></input><span>`c(1, 2, 3)`</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='0a54624b905011eb400b99e5e2de9435'></input><span>`seq(1, 3)`</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='0a54624b905011eb400b99e5e2de9435'></input><span>`matrix(1:3, nrow = 1)`</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Both `c()` and `seq()` create vectors. `matrix()` creates a matrix (even if 1-row). A list is not an atomic numeric vector.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


For `x <- c(10, 20, 30)`, which expressions return **20**? (Select all that apply)


<div class='webex-checkboxgroup' id='webex-4796677ef0ba775c471cc1227d92d499' data-answer='bwYVBhoHG1Q7'><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='4796677ef0ba775c471cc1227d92d499'></input><span>`x[2]`</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='4796677ef0ba775c471cc1227d92d499'></input><span>`x[1]`</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='4796677ef0ba775c471cc1227d92d499'></input><span>`x[3]`</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='4796677ef0ba775c471cc1227d92d499'></input><span>`x[x == 20]`</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Index 2 is 20, and logical subsetting `x == 20` returns 20. Indices 1 and 3 return 10 and 30.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Which objects are **vectors** in base R? Select all that apply.


<div class='webex-checkboxgroup' id='webex-528f0cd7fdc9d03bebc0104b1163c3ab' data-answer='bgMUVxxSSAc7'><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='528f0cd7fdc9d03bebc0104b1163c3ab'></input><span>`c(1, 2, 3)`</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='528f0cd7fdc9d03bebc0104b1163c3ab'></input><span>`1:10`</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='528f0cd7fdc9d03bebc0104b1163c3ab'></input><span>`c("a", "b")`</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='528f0cd7fdc9d03bebc0104b1163c3ab'></input><span>`matrix(1:6, nrow = 2)`</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Vectors include numeric/integer/character vectors (e.g., `c(1,2,3)`, `1:10`, `c("a","b")`). A matrix is a different class with two dimensions.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Write the base R function that creates a sequence with a chosen step size (e.g., by = 0.5).

<input class='webex-solveme regex' id='webex-f03c9b574809dda737cd70801b5b1b49' size='22' data-answer='PRJtP2URH0RRSRhlOEw9axoeXDhrQxIUEz8='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

`seq()` is the function that you can use to create sequences with flexible start/end/step values.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


In base R graphics, which function creates a scatterplot?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-deabf2428b1e22d5aafe5af65ec72428' data-answer='P1VNUkoDGAJl'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='deabf2428b1e22d5aafe5af65ec72428'></input><span>hist()</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='deabf2428b1e22d5aafe5af65ec72428'></input><span>barplot()</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='deabf2428b1e22d5aafe5af65ec72428'></input><span>plot()</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='deabf2428b1e22d5aafe5af65ec72428'></input><span>boxplot()</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

`plot(x, y)` is the standard base R scatterplot function when `x` and `y` are numeric vectors. `hist()` makes histograms, `boxplot()` boxplots, and `barplot()` bar charts.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Which expressions create sequences of values? Select all that apply.


<div class='webex-checkboxgroup' id='webex-788f53911e8f0cb2ab456ee27a359654' data-answer='bAkUVhkCFQBs'><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='788f53911e8f0cb2ab456ee27a359654'></input><span>`seq(1, 9, by = 2)`</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='788f53911e8f0cb2ab456ee27a359654'></input><span>`rep(1, 5)`</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='788f53911e8f0cb2ab456ee27a359654'></input><span>`1:5`</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='788f53911e8f0cb2ab456ee27a359654'></input><span>`seq(1, 5)`</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

`1:5` and `seq()` create sequences. `rep()` repeats values rather than stepping through a range.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Which base R function returns the number of rows of a matrix `m`?

<input class='webex-solveme regex' id='webex-41bab010bcc1ae2779e871a3466cfaca' size='23' data-answer='bxM8PT5DG14QDBQZPTkaa2sQTAdrbRIZEBRr'/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

`nrow()` is the function that returns the number of rows in matrix (also works for data frames).

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Write a base R expression that creates the integer sequence from 1 to 10 using a `:`.

<input class='webex-solveme regex' id='webex-22ad2abf7ebbd7a198153521e3d9defc' size='20' data-answer='aRBQXgNRQDs='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

`1:10` uses the colon operator to create an integer sequence from 1 to 10.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Suppose `x <- c("a", "b", "c")`. What does `x[c(TRUE, FALSE, TRUE)]` return?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-ee0c652c01c9616423eddf79171bbf94' data-answer='PlUcUxoEHlNt'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='ee0c652c01c9616423eddf79171bbf94'></input><span>"b"</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='ee0c652c01c9616423eddf79171bbf94'></input><span>"a" "b" "c"</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='ee0c652c01c9616423eddf79171bbf94'></input><span>"a" "c"</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='ee0c652c01c9616423eddf79171bbf94'></input><span>TRUE FALSE TRUE</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Logical indexing keeps elements where the logical vector is TRUE. Here, it keeps elements 1 and 3, returning `c("a", "c")`.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


In base R, if you call `plot(1:5, 1:5)`, how many points are plotted?

<input class='webex-solveme nospaces' id='webex-3c1fdb01916fc458000f6209c7170b4c' data-tol='0' size='20' data-answer='aEEERDk='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Both x and y have length = 5, so five points are plotted.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Let `x <- seq(0, 1, by = 0.25)`. How many numbers are produced?

<input class='webex-solveme nospaces' id='webex-3ec36dfc929065acb50e9b7d84b7f71f' data-tol='0' size='20' data-answer='aEdWEWs='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

The sequence is 0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1. That is 5 numbers.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Which of the following are examples of **missing values** in R? Select all that apply.


<div class='webex-checkboxgroup' id='webex-c0bd2021a393a027bc4ef239e33e095e' data-answer='OAFOVB4BHgE8'><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='c0bd2021a393a027bc4ef239e33e095e'></input><span>`NA`</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='c0bd2021a393a027bc4ef239e33e095e'></input><span>`""` (empty string)</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='c0bd2021a393a027bc4ef239e33e095e'></input><span>`NaN`</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='c0bd2021a393a027bc4ef239e33e095e'></input><span>`NULL`</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

`NA` is the standard missing value in R. `NaN` can arise from undefined numeric operations (e.g., `0/0`). `NULL` means “no value” and `""` is an empty string, not missing.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


You have an RStudio Project with a `data/` folder. Which path is **portable** across computers if you share your RStudio project with a colleague?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-f003c8649bb80d2921cd6b1c9b6efcd3' data-answer='PQAcA08JGgRk'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='f003c8649bb80d2921cd6b1c9b6efcd3'></input><span>penguins.csv</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='f003c8649bb80d2921cd6b1c9b6efcd3'></input><span>C:/Users/Eduardo/Desktop/course/data/penguins.csv</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='f003c8649bb80d2921cd6b1c9b6efcd3'></input><span>data/penguins.csv</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='f003c8649bb80d2921cd6b1c9b6efcd3'></input><span>/Users/eduardo/Desktop/course/data/penguins.csv</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

`data/penguins.csv` is a relative path within the project, so it works as long as the same project structure exists in different computers. Absolute paths (starting with a drive letter or `/Users/...`) typically break on other computers.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Write the function that changes the working directory.

<input class='webex-solveme regex' id='webex-3dabec7d6f0a5fa5b14e1a4a726abb87' size='24' data-answer='aEY/PjkQHRdTEkcFHTo9HT5tHUwOPWgSHRYUPA=='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

`setwd()` is the function that changes the working directory for the current R session.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Write the base R command that reports how many elements a vector `x ` has.

<input class='webex-solveme regex' id='webex-2b6c4715d050afafff1c4586f3979177' size='23' data-answer='aUBoP2hEG1kBXlJECTo9Th46bUpoaUscQhFk'/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

`length(x)` returns the number of elements in `x`.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Let `x <- c(3, 5, 7, 9)`. What is `length(x)`?

<input class='webex-solveme nospaces' id='webex-1708a472c0b4b7b9142a29247e1993b5' data-tol='0' size='20' data-answer='ahUEGjw='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

A vector with four entries has length 4. `length()` counts elements, not values.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Let `x <- rep(5, times = 6)`. What is `length(x)`?

<input class='webex-solveme nospaces' id='webex-f57d2b1c560233430b81d0ce0747b2fc' data-tol='0' size='20' data-answer='PRcBRm8='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

`rep(5, times = 6)` repeats 5 six times.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Which statement about the R **workspace** is true?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-329b976ca5069a8648e34bb67a0a6595' data-answer='aAMVUhUHGlM8'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='329b976ca5069a8648e34bb67a0a6595'></input><span>The workspace is the set of objects currently in memory (Environment).</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='329b976ca5069a8648e34bb67a0a6595'></input><span>The workspace is a folder on disk that always matches your working directory.</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='329b976ca5069a8648e34bb67a0a6595'></input><span>The workspace is the same thing as the Console.</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='329b976ca5069a8648e34bb67a0a6595'></input><span>The workspace is the same thing as your script file.</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

In R, the workspace refers to objects currently in memory (e.g., vectors, data frames) shown in the Environment tab of RStudio. Files live on disk; scripts are text files; the Console is where commands run.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Which code creates a 2×3 matrix?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-02de227a6f69dc451bd98a38e9fd064c' data-answer='awJIVB4CG1Fr'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='02de227a6f69dc451bd98a38e9fd064c'></input><span>matrix(1:6, nrow = 3, ncol = 2)</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='02de227a6f69dc451bd98a38e9fd064c'></input><span>matrix(1:6, nrow = 2, ncol = 3)</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='02de227a6f69dc451bd98a38e9fd064c'></input><span>cbind(1:2, 3:4, 5:6)</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='02de227a6f69dc451bd98a38e9fd064c'></input><span>rbind(1:3, 4:6)</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

`matrix(1:6, nrow = 2, ncol = 3)` creates 2 rows and 3 columns, filling down columns by default. The others either have different shapes or build the matrix by binding.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Write a function that lists files in the current working directory in base R.

<input class='webex-solveme regex' id='webex-2e43d98da6d0755718508259b6fb792d' size='40' data-answer='aUdqbzhKEkwNXxdEa2kbUVhUUEMQbmkRPmpPSwhFVg1ATWhvTGVkTUgJTWxrRh8TE2U='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

`dir()` or `list.files()` returns a character vector of file and folder names in the current directory (or a specified path).

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Which function returns the current working directory?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-063c6d3f2c4e7847cc67895111ff6844' data-answer='awYfUhpUH1Zv'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='063c6d3f2c4e7847cc67895111ff6844'></input><span>list.files()</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='063c6d3f2c4e7847cc67895111ff6844'></input><span>getwd()</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='063c6d3f2c4e7847cc67895111ff6844'></input><span>dir.create()</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='063c6d3f2c4e7847cc67895111ff6844'></input><span>setwd()</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

`getwd()` returns the current working directory as a character string. `setwd()` changes it; `list.files()` lists contents; `dir.create()` creates a folder.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


For `m <- matrix(1:6, nrow = 2)`, what does `m[2, 3]` return?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-bbd3dc4d4f0b4a5bb6638c3c0eb66204' data-answer='OVJIAkhTGFRp'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='bbd3dc4d4f0b4a5bb6638c3c0eb66204'></input><span>5</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='bbd3dc4d4f0b4a5bb6638c3c0eb66204'></input><span>6</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='bbd3dc4d4f0b4a5bb6638c3c0eb66204'></input><span>4</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='bbd3dc4d4f0b4a5bb6638c3c0eb66204'></input><span>2</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

The matrix is filled by column: columns are (1,2), (3,4), (5,6). Row 2, column 3 is 6.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
